Multiple regression analysis with a dataset on automobiles

Goal: analyse what is the best model to predict cceleration (accel, sec -from 0 to 100km/h) when you have two potential important covariates: engine power (potenzacv, horsepower) and massa (massa, kg).

Data importing and cleaning

  1. Import data (in ‘automobili.Rdata’) and form your current dataset of interest.

Model representation (with multiple covariates)

  1. First, you can represent the fitted model by plotting (y^,y)(y^,y) or (y^,e)(y^,e) and check the deviance of points from the respective ideal line.
plot(predicted y, y)
abline(0, 1)
plot(predicted y, residuals)
abline(???)

Now, let’s represent yy as function of the covariates.

Using g(z)=β0+β1(1/z√)+x¯2g(z)=β0+β1(1/z)+x¯2 or g(x)=β0+β1(1/z¯−−√)+xg(x)=β0+β1(1/z¯)+x produces plots that are not straightforwardly interpretable. (Red dashes represent y^y^.)

Instead, we can separate the contribute of individual covariates by fitting a line on the residuals of yy and each xx once fitted a regression model on the remaining covariates.

fitYV = lm(accel ~ massa, data = d)
fitXV = lm(I(1/sqrt(potenzacv)) ~ massa, data = d)

plot(resid(fitYV) ~ resid(fitXV))
abline(h = 0, lty = 2)
abline(v = 0, lty = 2)
abline(lm(resid(fitYV) ~ resid(fitXV)))
summary(lm(resid(fitYV) ~ resid(fitXV)))
